title: "Lateralus on Bare Metal"
author: bad-antics
date: 2026-04-06
abstract: Running Lateralus programs on LateralusOS without any OS underneath requires a deep understanding of the syscall interface, memory model, and what it takes to go freestanding.

## The Basics

We're going to dive straight into the details. If you're not familiar with Lateralus or its underlying architecture, you might want to brush up on those topics before proceeding.

### The Syscall Interface

The syscall interface is a crucial component of any operating system. In our case, we need to define how processes interact with the hardware. The syscall interface provides a standardized way for programs to request services from the OS.

// syscalls.h
fn syscall(int32_t code: int): int {
    // Implementation-specific logic here
    return 0;
}

Note that this is a highly simplified example. Real-world syscall interfaces are much more complex and involve multiple stages.

## Memory Model

Memory management is another critical aspect of building an OS. We need to understand how to allocate, deallocate, and protect memory for each process.

// memlayout.h
struct MemLayout {
    // Page size
    const int pageSize = 4096;

    // Number of pages
    const int numPages = 1024;

    // Virtual address space size
    const int vaddrSpaceSize = pageSize * numPages;

    fn mapVirtualAddr(vaddr: int, paddr: int) -> bool {
        // Mapping logic here
        return true;
    }
}

## Going Freestanding

So far, we've covered the basics of the syscall interface and memory model. Now it's time to talk about what it takes to build a truly freestanding OS.

### The Boot Process

The boot process is where things get really interesting. We need to create a self-contained environment that can start executing from scratch.

// init.c
fn main() {
    // Boot up the hardware
    bootup();

    // Initialize the memory layout
    MemLayout.init();

    // Map virtual addresses
    MemLayout.mapVirtualAddr(0, 0);

    // Start executing the kernel code
    loop();
}

fn bootup() {
    // Boot up the hardware using Lateralus-specific instructions
    bootupInstructions();
}

